<HEADLINE>
<P>
DO IT!: COASTWALK'S ON TRAIL FOR MORE HIKERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICK VANDERKNYFF, Rick VanderKnyff is a member of The Times Orange County 
Edition staff. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Last year, more than 50 people spent four days walking the Orange County coast 
from San Clemente to Crystal Cove in the county's first involvement in a 
growing statewide movement called Coastwalk. This year, the event is back -- 
and looking for more participants. 
</P>
<P>
 Coastwalk will go this time from Sept. 15 through 18 and take walkers from the 
canyons and ridges of Laguna Coast Wilderness Park all the way north to the 
Bolsa Chica wetlands. Along the way, participants will get to walk and camp in 
some areas of coastal Orange County that are normally off-limits to the public. 
</P>
<P>
 But not just wilderness is on the agenda. Included are Balboa Island and some 
piers and beachside areas. 
</P>
<P>
 Cost is $30 a day. Gear will be shuttled from campsite to campsite. Dinner 
will be provided, but walkers will be responsible for their own camp breakfast 
and lunch. The trip will be limited to 40 people, but at last check it was less 
than half-full. 
</P>
<P>
 Participants in last year's walk enthusiastically embraced the chance to get a 
more intimate look at the local coast.  
</P>
<P>
 "I've always been interested in those canyons back there, living in Orange 
County for so long," said one man, walking the sands north of San Clemente. 
"This is a chance to see them." 
</P>
<P>
 Coastwalk started in 1983 with a hike along Sonoma County's coastline and has 
expanded to other counties every year since. With the addition of Ventura and 
Los Angeles counties, this is the first year the entire coast will be covered. 
Coastwalk is a nonprofit organization that works to increase awareness of the 
state's coastal resources and to lobby for a creating a trail along all 1,000 
miles of California coastline. 
</P>
<P>
 Advance registration is required. Organizers may allow some people to sign up 
for only part of the walk. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 If you've always seen those huge blimp hangars at Tustin Marine Corps 
Helicopter Air Station from a distance, and wanted a closer look, there's a 
chance coming Sunday. That's the day the base sponsors a 5K/10K run that 
actually goes through one of the wooden hangars. 
</P>
<P>
 Besides the run, there's an open house with displays and demonstrations of 
military hardware. Entry is $20 (including a T-shirt); race day registration is 
from 6 to 7:30 a.m. Both runs start at 8 a.m. For information, call (714) 
726-7531. 
</P>
<P>
 What: Orange County Coastwalk. 
</P>
<P>
 When: Sept. 15 to Sept. 18. 
</P>
<P>
 Where: From Laguna Coast Wilderness Park to Bolsa Chica State Ecological 
Reserve. 
</P>
<P>
 Whereabouts: Call organizers for details. 
</P>
<P>
 Wherewithal: $30 per day (includes dinner and transportation of gear). 
</P>
<P>
 Where to call: (310) 431-8600. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA090894-0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 076926 </DOCID>
