<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: OXNARD; TENTATIVE ACCORD AVERTS DUMP STRIKE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIGUEL BUSTILLO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A regional trash authority has reached a tentative contract with workers at 
the Bailard Landfill, averting a possible strike. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ventura County Regional Sanitation District, which operates the 
Oxnard-area dump, and the Service Employees International Union, which 
represents 34 workers at the landfill, came to terms Wednesday on a three-year 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
 Terms of the agreement were not immediately disclosed because details have not 
been worked out, Personnel Manager Arlene Morrelli said. 
</P>
<P>
 "We still have a lot of work to do," she said. "It's not quite over." 
</P>
<P>
 Union representatives did not return calls. 
</P>
<P>
 Workers are set to vote on the proposed contract Friday, and the results will 
be released Monday or Tuesday, Morrelli said. 
</P>
<P>
 The sanitation district and union have been discussing a contract for the 
workers since February. The union had voted to strike if necessary, and the 
district had vowed to hire outside workers to keep the dump open. MIGUEL 
BUSTILLO 
</P>
</TEXT>
