<DOCNO> LA090894-0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 077002 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
September 8, 1994, Thursday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 1; Column 5; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
283 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIMPSON'S EX-IN-LAWS ASSUME CHILD CUSTODY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By REBECCA TROUNSON, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 O.J. Simpson has agreed to transfer temporary legal guardianship of his two 
children to Louis and Juditha Brown of Dana Point, the parents of his slain 
ex-wife. 
</P>
<P>
 Louis Brown said Wednesday that Simpson's agreement formalizes an earlier 
understanding between the former football star and the Browns about the 
children. 
</P>
<P>
 Sydney Simpson, 8, and Justin Simpson, 6, have been living with their maternal 
grandparents in Monarch Bay since June, when Nicole Brown Simpson and her 
friend Ronald Goldman were found slain outside her Brentwood condominium. 
</P>
<P>
 O.J. Simpson has pleaded not guilty to the slayings. His trial is scheduled to 
begin Sept. 26. 
</P>
<P>
 Louis Brown said the agreement, filed in Orange County Superior Court in 
Orange last week, formally spells out details of the children's care that were 
not addressed in a letter Simpson gave his former in-laws in mid-June. 
</P>
<P>
 The Browns filed a petition on July 27 seeking legal guardianship of the 
children. 
</P>
<P>
 "The letter didn't give us enough leeway to take care of the children in any 
kind of emergency, to enroll them in school, to do other things that we need to 
do to take care of them," Brown said Wednesday. "It apparently didn't include 
enough details." 
</P>
<P>
 He said he expected to learn today whether the court would approve the 
arrangement without a hearing, which had been set for next Monday. "We'd like 
to avoid the publicity," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 The court document, signed by Simpson, the Browns and their attorneys, states 
that the Browns are seeking temporary guardianship until Simpson "is able to 
resume his legal and physical custody . . . upon his release from 
incarceration," the document states. 
</P>
<P>
 Associated Press contributed to this report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
