<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA; U.N. DENIES TELLING POPE TO CANCEL VISIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The United Nations denied that it told Pope John Paul II to cancel his visit 
to Sarajevo.The Pope's visit to the capital, planned for today, was called off 
after Bosnian Serbs refused to guarantee his safety and fired mortars around 
the city. Bosnia's Muslim leaders accused U.N. officials of recommending that 
the visit be put off, but the U.N. Protection Force said it had merely warned 
the Vatican of the risks. A leader of the Serbian Orthodox Christian Church in 
Bosnia expressed satisfaction that the Pope had called off his trip. "As far as 
I'm concerned, we don't need him. It doesn't please us to see him around," 
Metropolitan Bishop Vasilije said. 
</P>
