<P>
'SHOOTIST' BANK HOLDUP SUSPECTS PLEAD GUILTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A prolific bank robber known as "the Shootist" pleaded guilty Wednesday to 
committing one armed robbery and agreed to admit to four others. 
</P>
<P>
 Johnny Madison Williams Jr., 43, and his wife, Carolyn Marie Williams, 34, are 
suspected of taking more than $750,000 in 56 banks robberies over eight years 
in California, Washington and Texas.Among the crimes were robberies in Irvine, 
Laguna Niguel, San Juan Capistrano and Mission Viejo. 
</P>
<P>
 The Williamses pleaded guilty Wednesday to one count of armed robbery and one 
count of use of a firearm in a 1991 holdup at a First Interstate Bank branch in 
the Seattle suburb of Bellevue. 
</P>
<P>
 They agreed to plead guilty to four additional counts of armed bank robbery in 
cases in California and Texas, said Assistant U.S. Atty. Robert Chadwell. They 
also agreed to plead guilty to one count of conspiracy that will cover all 56 
robberies, Chadwell said. 
</P>
<P>
 Johnny Williams will face a maximum sentence of 215 years in prison for the 
crimes in the three states and his wife will face up to 135 years, the U.S. 
attorney's office said. 
</P>
<P>
 In a typical holdup, Johnny Williams would enter the bank, announce the 
robbery, jump over the counter and fire a pistol shot into the ceiling while 
demanding money from bank employees, the FBI said. The getaway car often was 
driven by his wife, authorities said. 
</P>
