<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: THE REGION; FREEWAY EXTENSION BILL AWAITS OK BY GOVERNOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A bill that would allow Caltrans to build the long-delayed extension of the 
Long Beach (710) Freeway through South Pasadena without the city's agreement 
has reached the governor's desk. 
</P>
<P>
 The Assembly last week gave final legislative approval to the bill by 
Assemblywoman Diane Martinez (D-Monterey Park).The bill removes time limits in 
1982 legislation that allows for construction of a freeway through a city 
without its permission where a deadlock has existed for more than 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
 Last September, a Sacramento judge ruled that the 1982 legislation, authored 
by Martinez's father, U.S. Rep. Matthew G. Martinez (D-Monterey Park) when he 
was a state legislator, had lapsed because Caltrans failed to complete an 
environmental report in the time specified by the law. 
</P>
<P>
 The California Transportation Commission will consider giving final approval 
to the $805-million project next week. The Federal Highway Administration, 
which will provide 85% of the funding, would then decide on whether to proceed 
with the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
