<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: POMONA; BLACKS ASKED TO DONATE BONE MARROW FOR GIRL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 American Red Cross officials have issued a plea for African Americans to 
volunteer as potential bone marrow donors to save the life of a 4-year-old 
Pomona girl suffering from a rare blood disease. 
</P>
<P>
 A marrow drive will be conducted in Pomona throughout the weekend at the Los 
Angeles County Fair and at a local church in hopes of finding a matching donor 
for the youngster, a black girl who was diagnosed two years ago as having a 
degenerative genetic disease called mucopoly saccharidosis, said Jackie 
Ramirez, a Red Cross senior recruiter. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials said potential donors have been particularly difficult to identify 
because African Americans account for only about 5% of the more than 1 million 
donors registered in the National Marrow Donor Program. The chances of finding 
a matching donor are greatest within a similar ethnic group. 
</P>
<P>
 The marrow donor testing will be conducted Saturday and Sunday from 9 a.m. to 
4 p.m. at Club House I at the County Fairgrounds, 1101 W. McKinley Ave., and on 
Sunday from 1:15 to 4 p.m. at Macedonia Baptist Church, 710 S. Hamilton St. 
Additional information is available by calling the Marrow Donor Program at 
(800) MARROW-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
