<HEADLINE>
<P>
AN ENTERPRISING CAREER CHANGE; ENTREPRENEUR: STORE TARGETS STAR TREK FANS. 
OWNER LOVES HIS WORK AND IS TURNING A SMALL PROFIT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JON NALICK, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Jerry Lazar has boldly gone where few have gone before, and he's doing a brisk 
business there. 
</P>
<P>
 Lazar recently opened a store in Santa Ana devoted to Star Trek memorabilia. 
"It's sort of like a mini-convention, but there's no cover charge or two-drink 
minimum," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Lazar, 40, opened The Trekker about three months ago after leaving a 20-year 
career as an escrow officer for several companies, including his family's Lazar 
Escrow in Long Beach. 
</P>
<P>
 "I like fun stuff," he said. "We don't take things seriously here, and that's 
why I'm here. I'm tired of being an adult." 
</P>
<P>
 He started the shop with $40,000 he received from an inheritance. Since then, 
more than 1,300 customers have come through the doors, he said. He projects 
sales for his first year in business to top $60,000. 
</P>
<P>
 The store is already turning a small profit of about $800 a month, said Lazar, 
who is the sole owner and employee. 
</P>
<P>
 Situated at 2431 N. Tustin Ave, Suite M, the shop offers crystal Enterprise 
paperweights, Bajoran-style earrings, masks and posters. There are life-size 
cutouts of Capt. Kirk., Mr. Spock, Capt. Picard and other members of the 
Enterprise crew. The shop also features uniforms from the original series, 
"Star Trek: The Next Generation" and "Deep Space Nine." 
</P>
<P>
 The most expensive items are limited-edition lithographs of the Enterprise 
hurtling past exploding planets. One lithograph, autographed by Patrick 
Stewart, the actor who plays Picard, sells for $600. 
</P>
<P>
 Cindy Chasse of Irvine spent a recent lunch hour at the store browsing for 
Trek trinkets. 
</P>
<P>
 Chasse, 32, said that when she first heard the store was opening, "I said, 
'I've got to go there and see what they have.' " 
</P>
<P>
 She said that the store doesn't match the variety of memorabilia available at 
Star Trek conventions. However, it offers hard-to-find items such as the 
lithographs. For collectors, she said, "this place is great. Absolutely great." 
</P>
<P>
 During her visit, Chasse bought several items, including a magnetic puzzle 
displaying a holographic image of the Enterprise and other star ships. 
</P>
<P>
 "I also got a glow-in-the-dark Enterprise. I have glow-in-the-dark stars in my 
room, and I needed an Enterprise for it," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 Dressed in the blue and black uniform of a Starfleet medical officer, Lazar 
said that when he was considering starting a business, he was unsure what 
direction to take. 
</P>
<P>
 "I asked myself, 'What do I really have a passion for?' The answer was Star 
Trek and the Lakers, but the way they've been playing, I figured it would be 
too hard to make money off the Lakers." 
</P>
</TEXT>
