<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: LONG BEACH; CITY COLLEGE RECEIVES $1.7-MILLION U.S. GRANT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN D. WAGNER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Long Beach City College has been awarded a $1.7-million federal grant for 
programs to help underachieving students stay in school. 
</P>
<P>
 The grant from the Department of Education will pay for programs to evaluate 
and help students needing assistance in basic math, reading or 
writing.According to college officials, 85% of incoming students are not ready 
for college-level English courses, 67% need help with reading skills and 84% 
need instruction in basic math. Last fall, 4,400 students were placed on 
probation or were dismissed. College enrollment was about 24,000. 
</P>
<P>
 As part of the effort, counselors will line up tutoring for students and will 
keep track of students' progress. Groups of students also will be assigned to 
the same classes and encouraged to study together. 
</P>
<P>
 Faculty members will receive training about the many cultures at the school. 
JOHN D. WAGNER 
</P>
</TEXT>
