<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOOTBALL '94 / HIGH SCHOOL COACHES SHOW OFF THEIR TRICKS!; SOUTHERN SECTION; 
GOLDEN LEAGUE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ANTELOPE VALLEY ANTELOPES 03,14,08,07 1993 OVERALL LEAGUE PLACE 7-6* 1-4* 5th 
03,15,06,18 COACH YR. RECORD AT SCHOOL Brent Newcomb 17th 120-74-1 
04,26,05,05,05 TOP RETURNEES OFF DEF YR Jermaine Lewis, 5-7, 155 TB DB Jr. 
Trymon Redick, 6-1, 180 QB DB Jr. Chad Shrout, 6-1, 230 P DL Sr. Caleb Smith, 
6-3, 215, OT DL Sr. Chad Murphy, 6-1, 170 WR DB Sr. David Dilger, 6-2, 255 OT 
DL Sr. 04,25,05,05,05 TOP NEWCOMERS OFF DEF YR Justin Reiner, 6-1, 196 FB LB 
Jr. Sean Cartaya, 6-1, 187 TE LB Jr. Ken Nelson, 5-8, 155 RB DB Jr. FAST FACT 
</P>
<P>
 The Antelopes reached the Division I playoffs despite forfeiting three league 
games, then defeated Bishop Amat, the top-ranked team in the state, 21-7, in 
the second round. 
</P>
<P>
 OUTLOOK 
</P>
<P>
 The Antelopes lose plenty from last year's Division I semifinal team, but two 
of their best players return. Lewis rushed for 1,612 yards (sixth-best in the 
area) and 19 touchdowns in 1993. Shrout averaged 46.9 yards a punt and is a 
preseason All-American according to several publications. "He's the first guy 
we've ever had whose gotten interest from schools east of the Mississippi," 
Newcomb said. Smith, a returning All-League selection, leads a defense which 
allowed only 10 points a game in league. HIGHLAND BULLDOGS 03,14,08,07 1993 
